Scored & Grilled Boneless Beef Short Ribs over the fire today! 🥩 🔪 🌿 🔥
.
A few weeks back, one of my friends described to me the process of scoring meat like a hassleback potato. For more tough cuts like beef short ribs, it helps the marinade tenderize the meat more and give a larger surface area to get a nice crust. I scored these boneless beef short ribs and let them marinate overnight in a soy sauce, sriracha, rice wine vinegar, sesame seed oil and Korean BBQ seasoning mixture. Grilled them for 4-5 minutes per side and glazed with some fish sauce for an extra tang right at the end. I pulled them off around 130F. They were super tender and delicious! Highly recommend this technique! Find more recipes like this on my blog: www.overthefirecooking.com!🍻 👍
.
.
.
Steaks:
- 5-6 Boneless Beef Short Rib filets
- Fish Sauce, for glaze 
- Scallions, for garnish 
- Sesame Seeds, for garnish
.
Marinade:
- 2 tbsp of Korean BBQ Seasoning
- 1/2 cup of Soy Sauce 
- 1/4 cup of Rice Vinegar
- 2 Limes, juiced
- 2 tsp of Sesame Seed Oil
.
Instructions:
1. Take your beef ribs and score them across about 1/4 inch deep on both sides.
3. In a food safe bowl, add your beef and marinade. Mix and set in fridge for 4 hours or ideally overnight.
4. Preheat your grill to medium-high temperature (around 375F).
5. Add steaks to grill and cook for about 4-5 minutes per side or until they are 130F internal. Towards the end, glaze with fish sauce for a nice finishing crust.
6. Pull steak off once done and rest for 7-8 minutes. Top with scallions, sesame seeds and enjoy!
.
.
.
#overthefirecooking

Lemon Chili Bacon Wrapped Chicken Skewers over the fire 🍗 🥓 🍋 🌶 🔥
.
For a while now, I have been wanting to make this recipe. After seeing some South American cooks use bacon wrapped chicken on skewers, I knew that it was on the to do list sooner than later. Seasoned these guys with my own version of Peri Peri Sauce. This is a spicy citrus sauce that goes really well on chicken. It also cuts through the fat of the bacon nicely to make a savory, spicy and citrusy flavor. Grilled over a medium to medium-low fire to prevent flare ups, this Lemon Chili Bacon Wrapped Chicken Skewers were a bomb recipe for the backyard. Cheers! 🍻 👍
.
.
.
Ingredients:
.
Chicken Skewers:
- 2 lbs of Chicken Breast, cubed
- 18-20 Bacon Slices, cut in half
- Lemon juice, garnish
- Cilantro, garnish
.
Lemon Chili Sauce
- 2 Whole Habaneros
- 4-5 Garlic Cloves
- 1/8 cup of Cilantro
- 2 tbsp of White Vinegar
- 1 tbsp of Chipotle Powder
- 1 tbsp Dried Oregano
- 1 Lemon, juiced
- Oil, as needed
.
Steps:
- In a blender, mix the Lemon Chili sauce until smooth. Reverse 1/8 cup of sauce, then mix the rest over the chicken. Marinate for at least 2 hours or ideally overnight.
- Preheat grill for 3 zone cooking at medium heat (around 300F). - Wrap the chicken in bacon them securely skewer. Fill skewer as best as possible.
- Place skewers on grill. Rotate as needed to prevent flare ups. Cook until the chicken reaches 165F internal.
- Once chicken is close to done, preheat your reserve marinade and baste over the top of the chicken. Once chicken is done, pull and let rest for 2-3 minutes.
- Top chicken with chopped cilantro and lemon juice. Slice and enjoy!
.
.
.

Charcoal from @cowboycharcoal
Skewers from @superskewers
.
.
.

Musician: Jef

Roasted Chicken Trompo for perfect, juicy and delicious chicken! 🍗🥙🔥
.
Roasted Chicken Trompo for some delicious tzatziki pita pockets! The best way to level up any meal is by packing it full of some amazing protein. Call me biased, but I’ve found that the best proteins are cooked over an open flame. Inspired by Shawarma, we start by marinating some chicken so I can cook it on a vertical spit and turn it into an incredibly delicious and nutritious meal. Don’t save this one for later, go ahead and try it now! Find the whole recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/roasted-chicken-trompo/ 🍻 👍
.

Grilled Picanha with Farofa for taste testing 🥩 🌿🔥
.
I have been told for a while now that I need to try farofa with my grilled picanha. So today, I set out to try and make farofa at home with this wagyu picanha. What is farofa? Farofa is toasted cassava flour that is generally found served with grilled meats. I have to say, it is impossible to find coarsely ground cassava here in Nashville, so I have to improvise. But in the end, I think this turned out pretty good. I will definitely be trying out making farofa again in another recipe. What is your family recipe for far-off??? Find more recipes like this on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/ 🍻 👍
.
.
#overthefirecooking

Seared Tuna Tataki swimming it’s way onto our feed today! 🐟🍣🔥
.
I love Seared Tuna Tataki and am actually surprised I haven’t done this recipe yet. Tataki is a Japanese style of cooking that uses really high heat to get a sear on the meat, leaving the middle rare. I splashed the tuna tataki with a citrus and soy sauce blend for the perfect dinner! Find the whole recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/seared-tuna-tataki 🍻 👍

Breakfast Skillet Platter to start off the weekend right! 🍳 🥓 🔥
.
I have been craving a massive breakfast for a little while! This is a good throwback to this delicious Breakfast Skillet Platter I made a couple months ago. Bacon, sausage, potatoes, mushrooms, eggs and more all for a hearty morning feast. Find the recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/breakfast-skillet-platter/ 🍻 👍
.
.
#overthefirecooking

node.text:
Venison Rack with Wild Herb Butter for something unique 🦌 🌿 🔥
.
Venison Rack with Wild Herb Butter for some familiar flavors on a new protein. We haven’t done much venison on this channel, so let’s talk about it for a second. Like most game meat, venison is a very lean meat. For this reason, we want to cook it slowly (careful not to overcook it) so that it’s tender when we go to serve the dish. Low and slow is the perfect game for a smoker, so that’s exactly what I did for this Venison Rack with Wild Herb Butter recipe. Find the whole recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/venison-rack-with-wild-herb-butter/ 🍻 👍
.
.
#overthefirecooking

Sticky Orange Ginger Pork Belly for a fun and quick dish 🍖 🍊 🌶 🔥
.
A classic throwback to one of my favorite ways to cook pork belly from @nationalporkboard. Seared off some belly in the cast iron skillet until the fat rendered and it was all very crispy. Pulled it out and discard the fat (we used it later don’t worry). Made a simple orange and ginger sauce then tossed the pork belly back into the skillet. Topped off with sesame seeds & chives for a nice finish Find more recipes like this on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/ 🍻 👍
.
.
Ingredients:
Pork Belly - 1 slab of pork belly cubed, 1 tsp of sesame seeds & 1 tsp of chopped chives.
Sauce - 1/2 cup of soy sauce, 1/4 cup of rice wine vinegar, 2.5 tbsp of honey, 2 tbsp of minced garlic, 1 tbsp of chili paste, 1 tbsp of ginger paste and 1 orange zested & juiced.
.
.

Grilled Filets with Chile Vinegar Sauce to switch things up! 🥩🌶 🍊🔥
.
Grilled Filets with Chile Vinegar Sauce are here and they’re taking our filet game to the next level! Inspired by Mexican Aguachile, I wanted to make something similar on steak but with some of my own twists. Grilled these filets until a nice medium rare, sliced and served with the sauce underneath. The citrus tang with the slight sourness of the vinegar really paired perfectly with the simple rub I used on these filets. These filets were so delicious that my wife and I ate all three steaks before we had time to make any sort of side dish… Just sayin’... Find the whole recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/grilled-filets-with-chile-vinegar-sauce/ 🍻 👍
.

Bacon Wrapped Maple Glazed Pork Tenderloin for the win! 🍖 🥓 🍁 🔥
.
This epic pork tenderloin was wrapped in bacon and smoked till 145F. Super tender and delicious, this is for sure a crowd pleaser for the weekend! Try it in your oven too if you do not have a smoker! Find the whole recipe on my blog: https://overthefirecooking.com/link-in-bio/ 🍻 👍
